The female has no black markings or grey crown. Its upperparts and head are brown with darker streaks around the mantle and a distinct pale [[supercilium]]. Its underparts are pale grey-brown. The female's bill is brownish-grey and becomes darker in breeding plumage approaching the black of the male's bill.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=116–117}}{{sfn|Clement|Harris|Davis|1993|p=444}}

Juveniles are similar to the adult female, but deeper brown below and paler above, with paler and less defined supercilia. Juveniles have broader buff feather edges, and tend to have looser, scruffier plumage, like moulting adults. Juvenile males tend to have darker throats and white postoculars like adult males, while juvenile females tend to have white throats. However, juveniles cannot be reliably sexed by plumage: some juvenile males lack any markings of the adult male, and some juvenile females have male features. The bills of young birds are light yellow to [[straw (colour)|straw]], paler than the female's bill. Immature males have paler versions of the adult male's markings, which can be very indistinct in fresh plumage. By their first breeding season, young birds generally are indistinguishable from other adults, though they may still be paler during their first year.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=116–117}}{{sfn|Clement|Harris|Davis|1993|p=444}}

===Voice===
Most house sparrow [[bird vocalization|vocalisations]] are variations on its short and frequent chirping call. Transcribed as ''chirrup'', ''tschilp'', or ''philip'', this note is made as a contact call by flocking or resting birds; or by males to proclaim nest ownership and invite pairing. In the breeding season, the male gives this call repetitively, with emphasis and speed, but not much rhythm, forming what is described either as a song or an "ecstatic call" similar to a song.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=26–30}}{{sfn|Cramp|Perrins|1994|p=291}} Young birds also give a true song, especially in captivity, a warbling similar to that of the [[European greenfinch]].{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|p=101}}

Aggressive males give a trilled version of their call, transcribed as "chur-''chur-r-r-it-it-it-it''". This call is also used by females in the breeding season, to establish dominance over males while displacing them to feed young or incubate eggs.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=30–31}} House sparrows give a nasal alarm call, the basic sound of which is transcribed as ''quer'', and a shrill ''chree'' call in great distress.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=31–32}} Another vocalisation is the "appeasement call", a soft ''quee'' given to inhibit aggression, usually given between birds of a mated pair.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=30–31}} These vocalisations are not unique to the house sparrow, but are shared, with small variations, by all sparrows.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|p=254}}

===Variation===
[[File:Indian sparrow (Passer domesticus indicus) immature Udaipur.jpg|thumb|upright|An immature of the Indian subspecies (''P.&nbsp;d. indicus'') in Rajasthan, India]]

Some variation is seen in the 12 subspecies of house sparrows, which are divided into two groups, the [[Indomalayan realm|Oriental]] ''P.&nbsp;d. indicus'' group, and the [[Palearctic realm|Palaearctic]] ''P.&nbsp;d. domesticus'' group. Birds of the ''P.&nbsp;d. domesticus'' group have grey cheeks, while ''P.&nbsp;d. indicus'' group birds have white cheeks, as well as bright colouration on the crown, a smaller bill, and a longer black bib.<ref name=amn/> The subspecies ''P.&nbsp;d. tingitanus'' differs little from the nominate subspecies, except in the worn breeding plumage of the male, in which the head is speckled with black and underparts are paler.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|p=117}} ''P.&nbsp;d. balearoibericus'' is slightly paler than the nominate, but darker than ''P.&nbsp;d. bibilicus''.{{sfn|Snow|Perrins|1998|pp=1061–1064}} ''P.&nbsp;d. bibilicus'' is paler than most subspecies, but has the grey cheeks of ''P.&nbsp;d. domesticus'' group birds. The similar ''P.&nbsp;d. persicus'' is paler and smaller, and ''P.&nbsp;d. niloticus'' is nearly identical but smaller. Of the less widespread ''P.&nbsp;d. indicus'' group subspecies, ''P.&nbsp;d. hyrcanus'' is larger than ''P.&nbsp;d. indicus'', ''P.&nbsp;d. hufufae'' is paler, ''P.&nbsp;d. bactrianus'' is larger and paler, and ''P.&nbsp;d. parkini'' is larger and darker with more black on the breast than any other subspecies.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|p=117}}{{sfn|Clement|Harris|Davis|1993|p=445}}{{sfn|Roberts|1992|pp=472–477}}

===Identification===
The house sparrow can be confused with a number of other seed-eating birds, especially its relatives in the genus ''Passer''. Many of these relatives are smaller, with an appearance that is neater or "cuter", as with the [[Dead Sea sparrow]].{{sfn|Mullarney|Svensson|Zetterstrom|Grant|1999|pp=342–343}} The light brown-coloured female can often not be distinguished from other females, and is nearly identical to those of the [[Spanish sparrow|Spanish]] and [[Italian sparrow]]s.{{sfn|Clement|Harris|Davis|1993|p=444}} The [[Eurasian tree sparrow]] is smaller and slenderer with a chestnut crown and a black patch on each cheek.{{sfn|Clement|Harris|Davis|1993|pp=463–465}} The male Spanish sparrow and Italian sparrow are distinguished by their chestnut crowns. The [[Sind sparrow]] is very similar but smaller, with less black on the male's throat and a distinct pale supercilium on the female.{{sfn|Clement|Harris|Davis|1993|p=444}}

==Taxonomy and systematics==

===Names===
The house sparrow was among the first animals to be given a [[binomial nomenclature|scientific name]] in the modern system of [[biological classification]], since it was described by [[Carl Linnaeus]], in the 1758 [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|10th edition]] of ''[[Systema Naturae]]''. It was described from a [[type specimen]] collected in [[Sweden]], with the name ''Fringilla domestica''.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=121–122}}{{sfn|Linnaeus|1758|p=183}} Later, the genus name ''[[Fringilla]]'' came to be used only for the [[common chaffinch]] and its relatives, and the house sparrow has usually been placed in the genus ''Passer'' created by French zoologist [[Mathurin Jacques Brisson]] in 1760.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=114–115}}{{sfn|Brisson|1760|p=36}}

The bird's scientific name and its usual English name have the same meaning. The [[Latin]] word {{Lang|la|passer}}, like the English word "sparrow", is a term for small active birds, coming from a root word referring to speed.<ref>{{Cite EB1911|first=Alfred|last=Newton|authorlink=Alfred Newton|wstitle=Sparrow|volume=25}}</ref>{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|p=13}} The Latin word ''domesticus'' means "belonging to the house", like the common name a reference to its association with humans.{{sfn|Jobling|2009|p=138}} The house sparrow is also called by a number of alternative English names, including ''English sparrow'', chiefly in North America;<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of World Environmental History |editor=Krech III, Shepard |editor2=McNeill, John Robert |editor3=Merchant, Carolyn |volume=3 |title=House Sparrow |last=Saikku |first=Mikko |year=2004 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0-415-93735-1 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofwo0000unse }}</ref>{{sfn|Turcotte|Watts|1999|p=429}} and ''Indian sparrow'' or ''Indian house sparrow'', for the birds of the [[Indian subcontinent]] and [[Central Asia]].{{sfn|Sibley|Monroe|1990| pp=669–670}} Dialectal names include ''sparr'', ''sparrer'', ''spadger'', ''spadgick'', and ''philip'', mainly in southern England; ''spug'' and ''spuggy'', mainly in northern England; ''spur'' and ''sprig'', mainly in [[Scotland]];{{sfn|Lockwood|1984|pp=114–146}}{{sfn|Swainson|1885|pp=60–62}} and ''spatzie'' or ''spotsie'', from the German ''{{Lang|de|Spatz}}'', in North America.{{sfn|Carver|1987|pp=162, 199}}

===Taxonomy===
[[File:Passer italiae pair.jpg|thumb|right|A pair of [[Italian sparrow]]s, in Rome]]
The genus ''Passer'' contains about 25 species, depending on the authority, 26 according to the ''[[Handbook of the Birds of the World]]''.<ref name=HBW>{{cite book|first=J. Denis|last=Summers-Smith|editor=del Hoyo, Josep |editor2=Elliott, Andrew |editor3=Christie, David|contribution=Family Passeridae (Old World Sparrows)|title=Handbook of the Birds of the World. Volume 14: Bush-shrikes to Old World Sparrows|year=2009|location=Barcelona|publisher=Lynx Edicions|isbn=978-84-96553-50-7}}</ref> Most ''Passer'' species are dull-coloured birds with short, square tails and stubby, conical beaks, between {{convert|11 and 18|cm|abbr=on}} long.<ref name="Groschupf"/>{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=253–254}} [[Mitochondrial DNA]] studies suggest that [[speciation]] in the genus occurred during the [[Pleistocene]] and earlier, while other evidence suggests speciation occurred 25,000 to 15,000 years ago. Within ''Passer'', the house sparrow is part of the "[[Palaearctic]] black-bibbed sparrows" group and a close relative of the Mediterranean "willow sparrows".<ref name=HBW/><ref>{{cite conference |last=González |first=Javier |author2=Siow, Melanie |author3=Garcia-del-Rey, Eduardo |author4=Delgado, Guillermo |author5=Wink, Michael |title=Phylogenetic Relationships of the Cape Verde Sparrow based on Mitochondrial and Nuclear DNA |conference=Systematics 2008, Göttingen |year=2008 |url=http://www.avescanarias.com/pdfs/CO%20Garcia-del-Rey%20POSTER%20(PASIAG).pdf |archive-date=7 July 2011 |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707192833/http://www.avescanarias.com/pdfs/CO%20Garcia-del-Rey%20POSTER%20(PASIAG).pdf  }}</ref>

The taxonomy of the house sparrow and its Mediterranean relatives is complicated. The common type of "willow sparrow" is the Spanish sparrow, which resembles the house sparrow in many respects.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|p=164}} It frequently prefers wetter habitats than the house sparrow, and it is often colonial and nomadic.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|p=172}} In most of the Mediterranean, one or both species occur, with some degree of [[Hybrid (biology)|hybridisation]].{{sfn|Anderson|2006|p=16}} In North Africa, the two species hybridise extensively, forming highly variable mixed populations with a full range of characters from pure house sparrows to pure Spanish sparrows.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=126–127}}<ref name="Töpfer">{{cite journal|last=Töpfer|first=Till|year=2006|title=The Taxonomic Status of the Italian Sparrow – ''Passer italiae'' (Vieillot 1817): Speciation by Stabilised Hybridisation? A Critical Analysis|journal=[[Zootaxa]]|volume=1325|pages=117–145|issn=1175-5334|doi=10.11646/zootaxa.1325.1.8|s2cid=35687355}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Moineaux domestiques et Moineaux espagnols, ''Passer domesticus'' et ''P. hispaniolensis'', dans une région de l'ouest algérien: analyse comparative de leur morphologie externe|journal=Le Gerfaut |year=1986|author=Metzmacher, M.|volume=76|pages=317–334|language=fr, en}}</ref>

In most of Italy, the breeding species is the [[Italian sparrow]], which has an appearance intermediate between those of the house and Spanish sparrows. Its specific status and origin are the subject of much debate, but it may be a case of long-ago [[hybrid speciation]].<ref name="Töpfer"/>{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=13–18, 25–26}} In the [[Alps]], the Italian sparrow [[intergrade]]s over a narrow roughly {{convert|20|km|adj=on|abbr=on}} strip with the house sparrow, and some house sparrows migrate into the Italian sparrow's range in winter.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=121–126}} On the Mediterranean islands of [[Malta]], [[Gozo]], [[Crete]], [[Rhodes]], and [[Karpathos]], other apparently intermediate birds are of unknown status.<ref name="Töpfer"/>{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=169–170}}{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1992|pp=22, 27}}

===Subspecies===
[[File:Passer domesticus -Istanbul-8b.jpg|thumb|A male of the subspecies ''P.&nbsp;d. balearoibericus'' in [[Istanbul]]]]
[[File:Passer montanus Baikonur 001.jpg|thumb|A male of the migratory subspecies ''P.&nbsp;d. bactrianus'' (with a [[Eurasian tree sparrow]] and young house or Spanish sparrows) in [[Baikonur]], Kazakhstan]]
A large number of subspecies have been named, of which 12 were recognised in the ''Handbook of the Birds of the World''. These subspecies are divided into two groups, the Palaearctic ''P.&nbsp;d. domesticus'' group, and the Oriental ''P.&nbsp;d. indicus'' group.<ref name=HBW/> Several Middle Eastern subspecies, including ''P.&nbsp;d. biblicus'', are sometimes considered a third, intermediate group. The subspecies ''P.&nbsp;d. indicus'' was described as a species, and was considered to be distinct by many ornithologists during the 19th century.<ref name=amn>{{Cite journal|last=Vaurie|first=Charles |author2=Koelz, Walter|title=Notes on some Ploceidae from western Asia | journal = [[American Museum Novitates]]|issue=1406|hdl=2246/2345|year=1949 }}</ref>

Migratory birds of the subspecies ''P.&nbsp;d. bactrianus'' in the ''P.&nbsp;d. indicus'' group were recorded overlapping with ''P.&nbsp;d. domesticus'' birds without hybridising in the 1970s, so the Soviet scientists Edward I. Gavrilov and M. N. Korelov proposed the separation of the ''P.&nbsp;d. indicus'' group as a separate species.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=114–115}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Gavrilov|first=E. I.|year=1965|title=On hybridisation of Indian and House Sparrows|journal=[[Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club]]|volume=85|pages=112–4}}</ref> However, ''P.&nbsp;d. indicus'' group and ''P.&nbsp;d. domesticus'' group birds intergrade in a large part of [[Iran]], so this split is rarely recognised.<ref name=HBW/>

In North America, house sparrow populations are more differentiated than those in Europe.<ref name="evo-III">{{cite journal|title=Evolution in the House Sparrow. III. Variation in Size and Sexual Dimorphism in Europe and North and South America|last1=Johnston|first1=Richard F.|last2=Selander|first2=Robert K|journal=[[The American Naturalist]]|volume=107|issue=955|date=May–June 1973|pages=373–390|doi=10.1086/282841|jstor=2459538|bibcode=1973ANat..107..373J |s2cid=84083164}}</ref> This variation follows predictable patterns, with birds at higher latitudes being larger and darker and those in arid areas being smaller and paler.<ref name=Groschupf/>{{sfn|Oberholser|1974|p=1009}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Evolution in the House Sparrow. II. Adaptive Differentiation in North American Populations|last1=Johnston|first1=Richard F.|last2=Selander|first2=Robert K.|journal=Evolution|volume=25|issue=1|date=March 1971|pages=1–28|doi=10.2307/2406496|pmid=28562938|jstor=2406496}}</ref> However, how much this is caused by evolution or by environment is not clear.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Packard|first=Gary C.|title=House Sparrows: Evolution of Populations from the Great Plains and Colorado Rockies|date=March 1967|journal=Systematic Zoology|volume=16|issue=1|pages=73–89|doi=10.2307/2411519|jstor=2411519}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Johnston|first=R. F. |author2=Selander, R. K.|title=House Sparrows: Rapid Evolution of Races in North America | journal = Science| volume = 144 | issue = 3618 | pages = 548–550 |date = 1 May 1964 | doi =10.1126/science.144.3618.548|pmid=17836354|bibcode=1964Sci...144..548J|s2cid=31619378 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Selander|first1=Robert K.|last2=Johnston|first2=Richard F.|title=Evolution in the House Sparrow. I. Intrapopulation Variation in North America|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v069n03/p0217-p0258.pdf|volume=69|issue=3|year=1967|pages=217–258|journal=[[The Condor (journal)|The Condor]]|jstor=1366314|doi=10.2307/1366314 |bibcode=1967Condo..69..217S }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hamilton|first1=Suzanne|last2=Johnston|first2=Richard F.|title=Evolution in the House Sparrow—VI. Variability and Niche Width|journal=[[The Auk]]|date=April 1978|volume=95|issue=2|pages=313–323|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v095n02/p0313-p0323.pdf}}</ref> Similar observations have been made in New Zealand<ref>{{cite journal|last=Baker|first=Allan J.|date=July 1980|title=Morphometric Differentiation in New Zealand Populations of the House Sparrow (''Passer domesticus'')|journal=Evolution|volume=34|issue=4|pages=638–653|jstor=2408018|doi=10.2307/2408018|pmid=28563981}}</ref> and in South Africa.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=133–135}} The introduced house sparrow populations may be distinct enough to merit subspecies status, especially in North America and southern Africa,<ref name="HBW"/> and American ornithologist [[Harry Church Oberholser]] even gave the subspecies name ''P.&nbsp;d. plecticus'' to the paler birds of western North America.{{sfn|Oberholser|1974|p=1009}}

;''P. d. domesticus'' group
* ''P. d. domesticus'' <small>Linnaeus, 1758</small>, the [[nominate subspecies]], is found in most of Europe, across northern Asia to [[Sakhalin]] and [[Kamchatka]]. It is the most widely introduced subspecies.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=121–122}}
* ''P. d. balearoibericus'' <small>[[Adolf von Jordans|von Jordans]], 1923</small>, described from [[Mallorca]], is found in the [[Balearic Islands]], southern France, the [[Balkans]], and [[Anatolia]].<ref name=HBW/>
* ''P. d. tingitanus'' <small>([[Victor Loche|Loche]], 1867)</small>, described from [[Algeria]], is found in the [[Maghreb]] from [[Ajdabiya]] in [[Libya]] to [[Béni Abbès]] in Algeria, and to [[Morocco]]'s Atlantic coast. It hybridises extensively with the Spanish sparrow, especially in the eastern part of its range.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=126–128}}
* ''P. d. niloticus'' <small>Nicoll and Bonhote, 1909</small>, described from [[Faiyum]], Egypt, is found along the [[Nile]] north of [[Wadi Halfa]], Sudan. It intergrades with ''bibilicus'' in the [[Sinai Peninsula|Sinai]], and with ''rufidorsalis'' in a narrow zone around [[Wadi Halfa]]. It has been recorded in [[Somaliland]].{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=126–128}}{{sfn|Mackworth-Praed|Grant|1955|pp=870–871}}
* ''P. d. persicus'' <small>[[Nikolai Zarudny|Zarudny]] and Kudashev, 1916</small>, described from the [[Karun River]] in [[Khuzestan]], Iran, is found in the western and central Iran south of the [[Alborz]] mountains, intergrading with ''indicus'' in eastern Iran, and Afghanistan.<ref name=HBW/>{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=126–128}}{{sfn|Cramp|Perrins|1994|p=289}}
* ''P. d. biblicus'' <small>[[Ernst Hartert|Hartert]], 1910</small>, described from [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], is found in the Middle East from [[Cyprus]] and southeastern Turkey to the Sinai in the west and from [[Azerbaijan]] to [[Kuwait]] in the east.<ref name=HBW/>{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=126–128}}
;''P. d. indicus'' group
* ''P. d. hyrcanus'' <small>Zarudny and Kudashev, 1916</small>, described from [[Gorgan]], Iran, is found along the southern coast of the [[Caspian Sea]] from Gorgan to southeastern Azerbaijan. It intergrades with ''P.&nbsp;d. persicus'' in the Alborz mountains, and with ''P. d. bibilicus'' to the west. It is the subspecies with the smallest range.<ref name=HBW/>{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=126–128}}
* ''P. d. bactrianus'' <small>Zarudny and Kudashev, 1916</small>, described from [[Tashkent]], is found in southern Kazakhstan to the [[Tian Shan]] and northern Iran and [[Afghanistan]]. It intergrades with ''persicus'' in [[Baluchistan]] and with ''indicus'' across central Afghanistan. Unlike most other house sparrow subspecies, it is almost entirely migratory, wintering in the plains of the northern Indian subcontinent. It is found in open country rather than in settlements, which are occupied by the Eurasian tree sparrow in its range.<ref name=HBW/>{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=126–128}} There is an exceptional record from Sudan.<!-- South? think not, but needs to be checked -->{{sfn|Mackworth-Praed|Grant|1955|pp=870–871}}
* ''P. d. parkini'' <small>[[Hugh Whistler|Whistler]], 1920</small>, described from [[Srinagar]], [[Kashmir]], is found in the western [[Himalayas]] from the [[Pamir Mountains]] to southeastern [[Nepal]]. It is migratory, like ''P.&nbsp;d. bactrianus''.<ref name=amn/>{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=126–128}}
* ''P. d. indicus'' <small>[[Sir William Jardine, 7th Baronet|Jardine]] and [[Prideaux John Selby|Selby]], 1831</small>, described from [[Bangalore]], is found in the Indian subcontinent south of the Himalayas, in [[Sri Lanka]], western [[Southeast Asia]], eastern Iran, southwestern Arabia and southern [[Israel]].<ref name=amn/><ref name=HBW/>{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=126–128}}
* ''P. d. hufufae'' <small>[[Claud Buchanan Ticehurst|Ticehurst]] and [[Thomas Frederic Cheeseman|Cheeseman]], 1924</small>, described from [[Hofuf]] in [[Saudi Arabia]], is found in northeastern Arabia.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=126–128}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Vaurie|first=Charles|title=Systematic notes on Palearctic birds. No. 24, Ploceidae, the genera ''Passer'', ''Petronia'', and ''Montifringilla''|journal=American Museum Novitates|issue=1814|year=1956|hdl=2246/5394}}</ref>
* ''P. d. rufidorsalis'' <small>[[C. L. Brehm]], 1855</small>, described from [[Khartoum]], Sudan, is found in the Nile valley from Wadi Halfa south to [[Renk, South Sudan|Renk]] in northern [[South Sudan]],{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=126–128}}{{sfn|Mackworth-Praed|Grant|1955|pp=870–871}} and in eastern Sudan, northern Ethiopia to the [[Red Sea]] coast in [[Eritrea]].<ref name=HBW/> It has also been introduced to [[Mohéli]] in the [[Comoros]].{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|p=134}}

==Distribution and habitat==
[[File:House Sparrow nesting in saguaro cactus.JPG|thumb|upright|By a nest in a [[saguaro]] cactus in [[Arizona]], U.S.]]
[[File:Passer domesticus -Mount Cook, New Zealand.jpg|thumb|House sparrows perching on a roof, during winter in the [[Southern Alps (New Zealand)|Southern Alps]] of New Zealand]]

The house sparrow originated in the [[Middle East]] and spread, along with agriculture, to most of Eurasia and parts of North Africa.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=5, 9–12}} Since the mid-19th century, it has reached most of the world, chiefly due to deliberate introductions, but also through natural and shipborne dispersal.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=129–137, 280–283}} Its introduced range encompasses most of [[North America]] (including [[Bermuda]]),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://audubon.bm/bird/house-sparrow |title=House Sparrow: ''Passer domesticus'' |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Bermuda [[Audubon Society]] |publisher=Bermuda Audubon Society |access-date=2022-07-04 |quote=Status: Abundant naturalized species. Introduced in 1870 in belief that they would control flies in towns. A major threat to the breeding success of bluebirds. Local Habitat: Widespread in both built-up and in less developed areas. Habits: Nests February to July in roofs, cliffs, trees and bluebird boxes. Lays four to five brown speckled eggs.}}</ref> [[Central America]], southern South America, [[southern Africa]], part of [[West Africa]], [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], and islands throughout the world.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|p=5}} It has greatly extended its range in northern Eurasia since the 1850s,{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=171–173}} and continues to do so, as was shown by its colonisation around 1990 of [[Iceland]] and [[Rishiri Island]], Japan.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|p=22}} The extent of its range makes it the most widely distributed wild bird on the planet.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|p=5}}

===Introduction===
The house sparrow has become highly successful in most parts of the world where it has been introduced.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book |last=Long |first=John L. |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Introduced_Birds_of_the_World.html?id=fssQAQAAMAAJ |title=Introduced Birds of the World: The Worldwide History, Distribution and Influence of Birds Introduced to New Environments |date=1981 |publisher=Universe Books |isbn=978-0-87663-318-2 |language=en}}</ref> This is mostly due to its early adaptation to living with humans, and its adaptability to a wide range of conditions.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=293–296}}<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Martin|first1=Lynn B. II|last2=Fitzgerald|first2=Lisa|title=A taste for novelty in invading house sparrows, ''Passer domesticus''|year=2005|journal=Behavioral Ecology|volume=16|issue=4|pages=702–7|doi=10.1093/beheco/ari044|doi-access=free}}</ref> Other factors may include its ability to suppress costly inflammatory and behavioural responses to immune challenges in its non-native range<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Kelly |first=T. R. |last2=Lynch |first2=K. I. |last3=Cannon |first3=A. L. |last4=Couvillion |first4=K. E. |last5=Lattin |first5=C. R. |date=2025-04-08 |title=Behavioural infection tolerance of malaria is negatively correlated with pro-inflammatory cytokine expression in the brain of an invasive songbird |journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology |language=en |volume=79 |issue=4 |page=49 |doi=10.1007/s00265-025-03589-1 |issn=1432-0762}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Kelly |first=T. R. |last2=Cannon |first2=A. L. |last3=Stansberry |first3=K. R. |last4=Kimball |first4=M. G. |last5=Lattin |first5=C. R. |date=2024-01-01 |title=Changes in hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis function, immunity, and glucose during acute Plasmodium relictum infection in house sparrows (Passer domesticus) |journal=General and Comparative Endocrinology |volume=345 |article-number=114388 |doi=10.1016/j.ygcen.2023.114388 |issn=1095-6840 |pmid=37802425}}</ref>, compared to less-successful invaders like the [[Eurasian tree sparrow]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lee |first1=Kelly A. |last2=Martin |first2=((Lynn B., 2nd)) |last3=Wikelski |first3=Martin C. |year=2005 |url=http://www.princeton.edu/~wikelski/Publications/2005%20lee%20et%20al.pdf |title=Responding to inflammatory challenges is less costly for a successful avian invader, the house sparrow (''Passer domesticus''), than its less-invasive congener |journal=Oecologia |volume=145 |issue=2 |pages=244–251 |pmid=15965757 |doi=10.1007/s00442-005-0113-5  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060921034010/http://www.princeton.edu/~wikelski/Publications/2005%20lee%20et%20al.pdf |archive-date=21 September 2006 |bibcode=2005Oecol.145..243L |s2cid=13394657 }}</ref> Where introduced, it can extend its range quickly, sometimes at a rate over {{convert|230|km|abbr=on}} per year.{{sfn|Blakers|Davies|Reilly|1984|p=586}} In many parts of the world, it has been characterised as a pest, and poses a threat to native birds.<ref name=scapegoat/><ref>{{cite journal|last1= Clergeau|first1=Philippe|issue= 2|last2=Levesque|first2= Anthony|last3= Lorvelec|first3= Olivier|year=2004|volume=50|title=The Precautionary Principle and Biological Invasion: The Case of the House Sparrow on the Lesser Antilles|journal=International Journal of Pest Management|doi=10.1080/09670870310001647650|pages=83–89|citeseerx=10.1.1.603.208|s2cid=13123780}}</ref> A few introductions have died out or been of limited success, such as those to [[Greenland]], [[the Bahamas]], and [[Cape Verde]].<ref name="dist-changes"/><ref name=":0" />

The first of many successful introductions to North America occurred when birds from England were released in New York City, in 1852,{{sfn|Barrows|1889|p=17}}<ref name=Healy>{{cite journal|last=Healy|first=Michael |author2=Mason, Travis V. |author3=Ricou, Laurie|title='hardy/unkillable clichés': Exploring the Meanings of the Domestic Alien, ''Passer domesticus''|journal=Interdisciplinary Studies in Literature and Environment|volume=16|issue=2|year=2009|doi=10.1093/isle/isp025|pages=281–298}}</ref> intended to control the ravages of the [[Ellida caniplaga|linden moth]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/14/the-truth-about-sparrows/?_r=0|title=The Truth About Sparrows|last=Marshall|first=Peyton|website=Opinionator|access-date=2016-04-08|date=2014-05-14}}</ref> In North America, the house sparrow now occurs from the [[Northwest Territories]] of Canada to southern [[Panama]],<ref name="all about"/> and it is one of the most abundant birds of the continent.<ref name=scapegoat>{{cite web|last=Franklin|first=K.|title=The House Sparrow: Scourge or Scapegoat?|work=Naturalist News |publisher=Audubon Naturalist Society |year=2007 |url=http://www.audubonnaturalist.org/default.asp?page=674 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304002914/http://www.audubonnaturalist.org/default.asp?page=674|archive-date=4 March 2009 |access-date=17 December 2008}}</ref> 

The house sparrow was first introduced to Australia in 1863 at [[Melbourne]] and is common throughout the eastern part of the continent as far north as [[Cape York Peninsula|Cape York]],<ref name="dist-changes" /> but has been prevented from establishing itself in [[Western Australia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.agric.wa.gov.au/birds/sparrows?nopaging=1|website=Western Australia Department of Primary Industries and Regional Development|title=Sparrows|access-date=2018-10-07|date=2018-05-02}}</ref> where every house sparrow found in the state is killed.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Massam|first=Marion|title=Sparrows|journal=Farmnote|issue=117/99|url=http://www.agric.wa.gov.au/objtwr/imported_assets/content/pw/vp/bird/f11799.pdf|access-date=1 February 2009|issn=0726-934X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160318231354/https://www.agric.wa.gov.au/objtwr/imported_assets/content/pw/vp/bird/f11799.pdf|archive-date=18 March 2016}}</ref> House sparrows were introduced in New Zealand in 1859, and from there reached many of the Pacific islands, including [[Hawaii]].{{sfn|Anderson|2006|p=25}}

In southern Africa, birds of both the European subspecies (''P.&nbsp;d. domesticus'') and the Indian subspecies (''P.&nbsp;d. indicus'') were introduced around 1900.<ref name=":0" /> Birds of ''P.&nbsp;d. domesticus'' ancestry are confined to a few towns, while ''P.&nbsp;d. indicus'' birds have spread rapidly, reaching [[Tanzania]] in the 1980s. Despite this rapid spread, native relatives such as the [[Cape sparrow]] also occur and thrive in urban habitats.<ref name="dist-changes">{{cite book|last=Summers-Smith|first=J. D.|contribution=Changes in distribution and habitat utilisation by members of the genus ''Passer''|pages=11–29|title=Granivorous birds in the agricultural landscape|editor=Pinowski, J. |editor2=Summers-Smith, J. D.|year=1990|publisher=Pánstwowe Wydawnictom Naukowe|location=Warszawa|isbn=978-83-01-08460-8}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor=Harrison, J. A. |editor2=Allan, D. G. |editor3=Underhill, L. G. |editor4=Herremans, M. |editor5=Tree, A. J. |editor6=Parker, V. |editor7=Brown, C. J. |author=Brooke, R. K.|year=1997|contribution=House Sparrow|url=http://sabap2.adu.org.za/docs/sabap1/801.pdf|title=The Atlas of Southern African Birds|publisher=BirdLife South Africa|volume=1}}</ref> Separate introductions of house sparrows have occurred several other parts of Africa, including Kenya, where it is thought that sparrows were introduced to Mombasa around 1950.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=W. |first=Schrey, Aaron |last2=L. |first2=Liebl, Andrea |last3=L. |first3=Richards, Christina |last4=B. |first4=Martin, Lynn |date=2014-01-01 |title=Range Expansion of House Sparrows (Passer domesticus) in Kenya: Evidence of Genetic Admixture and Human-Mediated Dispersal |url=https://academic.oup.com/jhered/article/105/1/60/858787 |journal=Journal of Heredity |language=en |volume=105 |issue=1 |doi=10.1093/jhered/e |issn=0022-1503 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230613164347/https://academic.oup.com/jhered/article/105/1/60/858787 |archive-date=13 June 2023 |access-date=11 December 2025 |url-status=live }}</ref> 

In South America, it was first introduced near [[Buenos Aires]] around 1870, and quickly became common in most of the southern part of the continent.<ref name=":0" /> It now occurs almost continuously from [[Tierra del Fuego]] to the fringes of the [[Amazon basin]], with isolated populations as far north as coastal Venezuela.<ref name="dist-changes" />{{sfn|Lever|2005|pp=210–212}}{{sfn|Restall|Rodner|Lentino|2007|p=777}} The house sparrow is also established in the [[Falkland Islands]], where it arrived as a stowaway on [[whaling]] ships.<ref name=":0" />

===Habitat===
The house sparrow is closely associated with human habitation and cultivation.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=137–138}} It is not an obligate [[Commensalism|commensal]] of humans as some have suggested: birds of the migratory Central Asian subspecies usually breed away from humans in open country,{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=424–425}} and birds elsewhere are occasionally found away from humans.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=137–138}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Hobbs|first=J. N.|title=House Sparrow breeding away from Man|year=1955|volume=55|issue=4|journal=The Emu|url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/?act=view_file&file_id=MU955302.pdf|page=202|doi=10.1071/MU955202}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Wodzicki|first=Kazimierz|date=May 1956|title=Breeding of the House Sparrow away from Man in New Zealand|url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/?act=view_file&file_id=MU956143.pdf|journal=Emu|volume=54|issue=2|pages=146–7|doi=10.1071/mu956143e|bibcode=1956EmuAO..56..146W }}</ref> The only terrestrial habitats that the house sparrow does not inhabit are dense forest and [[tundra]]. Well adapted to living around humans, it frequently lives and even breeds indoors, especially in factories, warehouses, and zoos.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=137–138}} It has been recorded breeding in an English [[coal mine]] {{convert|640|m|abbr=on}} below ground,{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1992|pp=128–132}} and feeding on the [[Empire State Building]]'s observation deck at night.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v090n01/p0206-p0206.pdf|last=Brooke|first=R. K.|title=House Sparrows Feeding at Night in New York|journal=The Auk|volume=90|issue=1|date=January 1973|page=206}}</ref> It reaches its greatest densities in urban centres, but its reproductive success is greater in suburbs, where insects are more abundant.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=137–138}}<ref name=Poel/> On a larger scale, it is most abundant in wheat-growing areas such as the [[Midwestern United States]].{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|p=129}}

It tolerates a variety of climates, but prefers drier conditions, especially in moist tropical climates.<ref name="dist-changes"/>{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=137–138}} It has several adaptations to dry areas, including a high salt tolerance<ref>{{cite journal|last=Minock|first=Michael E.|year=1969|title=Salinity Tolerance and Discrimination in House Sparrows (''Passer domesticus'')
|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v071n01/p0079-p0080.pdf|volume=71|issue=1|pages=79–80|journal=The Condor|jstor=1366060|doi=10.2307/1366060}}</ref> and an ability to survive without water by ingesting [[berry|berries]].<ref name=Walsberg/> In most of eastern Asia, the house sparrow is entirely absent, replaced by the Eurasian tree sparrow.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Melville, David S. |author2=Carey, Geoff J. |year=1998 |title=Syntopy of Eurasian Tree Sparrow ''Passer montanus'' and House Sparrow ''P. domesticus'' in Inner Mongolia, China |journal=[[Forktail (journal)|Forktail]] |volume=13 |url=http://www.orientalbirdclub.org/publications/forktail/13pdfs/Melville-Sparrows.pdf |page=125 |access-date=10 September 2010  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110610175224/http://www.orientalbirdclub.org/publications/forktail/13pdfs/Melville-Sparrows.pdf |archive-date=10 June 2011 }}</ref> Where these two species overlap, the house sparrow is usually more common than the Eurasian tree sparrow, but one species may replace the other in a manner that ornithologist [[Maud Doria Haviland]] described as "random, or even capricious".{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|p=228}} In most of its range, the house sparrow is extremely common, despite some declines,<ref name=IUCN/> but in marginal habitats such as rainforest or mountain ranges, its distribution can be spotty.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=137–138}}

