===Social behaviour and social learning===
The house sparrow is a very social bird. It is gregarious during all seasons when feeding, often forming flocks with other species of birds.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|p=247}} It [[Roosting|roosts]] communally while breeding nests are usually grouped together in clumps. House sparrows also engage in social activities such as [[dust bath|dust]] or water bathing and "social singing", in which birds call together in bushes.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=139–142}}<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/jfo/v051n04/p0371-p0372.pdf|last=McGillivray|first=W. Bruce|title=Communal Nesting in the House Sparrow|journal=Journal of Field Ornithology|volume=51|year=1980|pages=371–2|issue=4}}</ref> The house sparrow feeds mostly on the ground, but it flocks in trees and bushes.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=139–142}} At feeding stations and nests, female house sparrows are dominant despite their smaller size, and they can fight over males in the breeding season.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Johnston|first=Richard F.|title=Aggressive Foraging Behavior in House Sparrows|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v086n03/p0558-p0559.pdf|journal=The Auk|volume=86|issue=3|pages=558–9|year=1969|doi=10.2307/4083421|jstor=4083421}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.2307/1366086|last=Kalinoski|first=Ronald|year=1975|title=Intra- and Interspecific Aggression in House Finches and House Sparrows|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v077n04/p0375-p0384.pdf|journal=The Condor|volume=77|issue=4|pages=375–384|jstor=1366086 |bibcode=1975Condo..77..375K }}</ref>

House sparrows also have strong social learning ability, for example about novel objects in their environments. Typically, house sparrows show a lot of variation in their responses to novel objects, foods, and environments, where some individual birds are willing to approach and explore novel items, whereas others stay away, a behaviour known as "[[neophobia]]."<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Kimball |first1=Melanie G. |last2=Gautreaux |first2=Eve B. |last3=Couvillion |first3=Kaitlin E. |last4=Kelly |first4=Tosha R. |last5=Stansberry |first5=Keegan R. |last6=Lattin |first6=Christine R. |date=2022-06-25 |title=Novel objects alter immediate early gene expression globally for ZENK and regionally for c-Fos in neophobic and non-neophobic house sparrows |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0166432822001310 |journal=Behavioural Brain Research |volume=428 |article-number=113863 |doi=10.1016/j.bbr.2022.113863 |pmid=35351483 |issn=0166-4328}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Dusang |first1=Blake A. |last2=Henry |first2=Marquise S. |last3=Kimball |first3=Melanie G. |last4=Cochran |first4=Ella B. |last5=Wilson |first5=Michael B. |last6=Lattin |first6=Christine R. |date=May 2025 |title=Spatial neophobia is still not correlated with object neophobia in wild-caught house sparrows ( Passer domesticus ) |journal=Royal Society Open Science |language=en |volume=12 |issue=5 |article-number=250220 |doi=10.1098/rsos.250220  |doi-access=free|issn=2054-5703 |pmc=12092101 |pmid=40400518 |bibcode=2025RSOS...1250220D }}</ref> Captive house sparrows learned about novel objects near their food dish (and changed their behaviour towards novel objects) both from observing another individual and from hearing recorded sparrow calls.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Kelly |first1=T. R. |last2=Kimball |first2=M. G. |last3=Stansberry |first3=K. R. |last4=Lattin |first4=C. R. |date=September 2020 |title=No, you go first: phenotype and social context affect house sparrow neophobia |journal=Biology Letters |language=en |volume=16 |issue=9 |article-number=20200286 |doi=10.1098/rsbl.2020.0286 |issn=1744-9561 |pmc=7532720 |pmid=32871090}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Kimball |first1=Melanie G. |last2=Masri |first2=Danna F. |last3=Gautreaux |first3=Eve B. |last4=Stansberry |first4=Keegan R. |last5=Kelly |first5=Tosha R. |last6=Lattin |first6=Christine R. |date=2024-07-30 |title=Conspecific alarm calls prevent the attenuation of neophobia behavior in wild-caught house sparrows (Passer domesticus) |journal=Frontiers in Bird Science |language=English |volume=3 |article-number=1440063 |doi=10.3389/fbirs.2024.1440063 |bibcode=2024FrBS....340063K |doi-access=free |issn=2813-3870}}</ref> 

===Sleep and roosting===
[[File:Alpenquai Zürich - Passer domesticus 2014-09-15 17-37-56.JPG|thumb|An immature house sparrow sleeping]]
House sparrows sleep with the bill tucked underneath the [[scapula]]r feathers.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Reebs|first1=S. G.|first2= N. |last2=Mrosovsky|year= 1990|title= Photoperiodism in house sparrows: testing for induction with nonphotic zeitgebers|journal=Physiological Zoology|volume= 63|issue=3|pages=587–599|doi=10.1086/physzool.63.3.30156230|s2cid=86062593}}</ref> Outside of the reproductive season, they often roost communally in trees or shrubs. Much communal chirping occurs before and after the birds settle in the roost in the evening, as well as before the birds leave the roost in the morning.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=139–142}} Some congregating sites separate from the roost may be visited by the birds prior to settling in for the night.<ref name=Poole/>

===Body maintenance===
Dust or water bathing is common and often occurs in groups. [[Anting (bird activity)|Anting]] is rare.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Potter|first=E. F. |year=1970|title= Anting in wild birds, its frequency and probable purpose|journal= Auk |volume=87|pages=692–713|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v087n04/p0692-p0713.pdf|doi=10.2307/4083703|issue=4|jstor=4083703 |bibcode=1970Auk....87..692P }}</ref> Head scratching is done with the leg over the drooped wing.<ref name=Poole/>

===Feeding===
[[File:House sparrow feeding grains.jpg|thumb|A female house sparrow feeding on rice grains]]
As an adult, the house sparrow mostly feeds on the seeds of [[cereal]]s and [[weed]]s, but it is opportunistic and adaptable, and eats whatever foods are available.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=273–275}} In towns and cities, it often scavenges for food in garbage containers and congregates in the outdoors of restaurants and other eating establishments to feed on leftover food and crumbs. It can perform complex tasks to obtain food, such as opening automatic doors to enter supermarkets,{{sfn|Anderson|2006|p=246}} clinging to hotel walls to watch vacationers on their balconies,<ref>{{cite journal|author=Kalmus, H.|title=Wall clinging: energy saving by the House Sparrow ''Passer domesticus''|year=1984|journal=Ibis|volume=126|issue=1|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1984.tb03667.x|pages=72–74}}</ref> and [[nectar robbing]] [[kowhai]] flowers.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Stidolph|first=R. D. H.|year=1974|title=The Adaptable House Sparrow|journal=Notornis|volume=21|issue=1|page=88|doi=10.63172/757168kjdaej |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/adaptable-house-sparrow|access-date=24 September 2011|archive-date=13 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713141731/http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/adaptable-house-sparrow}}</ref> In common with many other birds, the house sparrow requires [[gastrolith|grit]] to digest the harder items in its diet. Grit can be either stone, often grains of masonry, or the shells of eggs or [[snails]]; oblong and rough grains are preferred.{{sfn|Anderson|2006| pp=279–281}}<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.2307/1368983|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v097n01/p0057-p0067.pdf|last1=Gionfriddo|first1=James P.|last2=Best|first2=Louis B.|year=1995|title=Grit Use by House Sparrows: Effects of Diet and Grit Size|journal=The Condor|volume= 97|issue=1|pages=57–67|jstor=1368983 |bibcode=1995Condo..97...57G }}</ref>

Several studies of the house sparrow in temperate agricultural areas have found the proportion of seeds in its diet to be about 90%.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=273–275}}{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=34–35}}{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=159–161}} It will eat almost any seeds, but where it has a choice, it prefers cereals: [[oat]]s, [[wheat]] or [[maize]].{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|p=33}} Rural birds tend to eat more waste seed from animal dung and seed from fields while urban birds tend to eat more commercial bird seed and weed seed.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Jennifer |last1=Roof |url=https://animaldiversity.org/accounts/Passer_domesticus/ |title=''Passer domesticus'' house sparrow |website=Animal Diversity Web |publisher=University of Michigan Museum of Zoology}}</ref> In urban areas, the house sparrow also feeds largely on food provided directly or indirectly by humans, such as bread, though it prefers raw seeds.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=159–161}}<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Gavett, Ann P. |author2=Wakeley, James S. |year=1986|title=Diets of House Sparrows in Urban and Rural Habitats|journal=The Wilson Bulletin|volume=98|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v098n01/p0137-p0144.pdf}}</ref> The house sparrow also eats some plant matter besides seeds, including [[bud]]s, berries, and fruits such as grapes and cherries.<ref name=Walsberg>{{cite journal|doi=10.2307/1365787|last=Walsberg|first=Glenn E.|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v077n02/p0169-p0174.pdf|title=Digestive Adaptations of ''Phainopepla nitens'' Associated with the Eating of Mistletoe Berries|journal=The Condor|year=1975|volume=77|pages=169–174|issue=2|jstor=1365787}}</ref>{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=159–161}} In temperate areas, the house sparrow has an unusual habit of tearing flowers, especially yellow ones, in the spring.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=35, 38–39}}

Animals form another important part of the house sparrow's diet, chiefly [[insect]]s, of which [[beetle]]s, [[caterpillar]]s, [[diptera]]n flies, and [[aphid]]s are especially important. Various noninsect [[arthropod]]s are eaten, as are [[mollusc]]s and [[crustacean]]s where available, [[earthworm]]s, and even [[vertebrate]]s such as [[lizard]]s and [[frog]]s.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=273–275}} Young house sparrows are fed mostly on insects until about 15 days after hatching.{{sfn|Vincent|2005|pp=2–3}} They are also given small quantities of seeds, spiders, and grit. In most places, [[grasshopper]]s and [[cricket (insect)|crickets]] are the most abundant foods of nestlings.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=276–279}} [[Hemiptera|True bugs]], [[ant]]s, [[sawfly|sawflies]], and beetles are also important, but house sparrows take advantage of whatever foods are abundant to feed their young.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=276–279}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Ted R.|year=1977|title=Reproductive Responses of Sparrows to a Superabundant Food Supply|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v079n02/p0205-p0208.pdf|journal=The Condor|volume=79|pages=205–8|issue=2|jstor=1367163|doi=10.2307/1367163 |bibcode=1977Condo..79..205A }}</ref><ref name=Ivanov>{{cite book|last=Ivanov|first=Bojidar|contribution=Diet of House Sparrow [''Passer domesticus'' (L.)] nestlings on a livestock farm near Sofia, Bulgaria|pages=179–197|title=Granivorous birds in the agricultural landscape|editor=Pinowski, J. |editor2=Summers-Smith, J. D.|year=1990|publisher=Pánstwowe Wydawnictom Naukowe|location=Warszawa|isbn=978-83-01-08460-8}}</ref> House sparrows have been observed [[Kleptoparasitism|stealing]] prey from other birds, including [[American robin]]s.<ref name="all about"/>

The gut microbiota of house sparrows differs between chicks and adults, with [[Pseudomonadota]] (formerly Proteobacteria) decreasing in chicks when they get to around 9 days old, whilst the relative abundance of [[Bacillota]] increase.<ref>{{cite journal | author1= Kohl, K.D. |author2= Brun, A. | author3= Caviedes-Videl, E. | author4= Karasov, W.H. | year=2019| title= Age-related changes in the gut microbiota of wild House Sparrow nestlings | journal=Ibis| volume=161| pages = 184–191| doi= 10.1111/ibi.12618| issue=2| doi-access= free}}</ref>

===Locomotion===
The house sparrow's flight is direct (not undulating) and flapping, averaging {{convert|45.5|km/h|abbr=on}} and about 15&nbsp;wingbeats per second.<ref name=Poole/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Schnell| first1=G. D.|first2= J. J.|last2= Hellack|year=1978|title= Flight speeds of Brown Pelicans, Chimney Swifts, and other birds|journal=Bird-Banding |volume=49|pages=108–112|jstor= 4512338|doi=10.2307/4512338|issue=2}}</ref> On the ground, the house sparrow typically hops rather than walks. It can swim when pressed to do so by pursuit from predators. Captive birds have been recorded diving and swimming short distances under water.<ref name=Poole/>

=== Dispersal and migration ===
Most house sparrows do not move more than a few kilometres during their lifetimes. However, limited migration occurs in all regions. Some young birds disperse long distances, especially on coasts, and mountain birds move to lower elevations in winter.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=139–142}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Broun|first=Maurice|title=Apparent migratory behavior in the House Sparrow|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v089n01/p0187-p0189.pdf|journal=The Auk|volume=89|issue=1|year=1972|pages=187–9|doi=10.2307/4084073|jstor=4084073}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Waddington|first1=Don C.|last2=Cockrem|first2=John F.|journal=Notornis|volume=34|title=Homing Ability of the House Sparrow|url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/homing-ability-house-sparrow|year=1987|issue=1|page=57 |doi=10.63172/260196qsboyr |access-date=24 September 2011|archive-date=13 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713210838/http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/homing-ability-house-sparrow}}</ref> Two subspecies, ''P.&nbsp;d. bactrianus'' and ''P.&nbsp;d. parkini'', are predominantly [[bird migration|migratory]]. Unlike the birds in sedentary populations that migrate, birds of migratory subspecies prepare for migration by putting on weight.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=139–142}}

===Breeding===
[[File:House Sparrows mating I IMG 0066.jpg|thumb|A pair of the Indian subspecies (''P.&nbsp;d. indicus'') mating in [[Kolkata]]]]
House sparrows can breed in the breeding season immediately following their hatching, and sometimes attempt to do so. Some birds breeding for the first time in tropical areas are only a few months old and still have juvenile plumage.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=135–136}} Birds breeding for the first time are rarely successful in raising young, and reproductive success increases with age, as older birds breed earlier in the breeding season, and fledge more young.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Journal of Avian Biology|volume=38 |issue=5 |pages=603–611|year=2007 |title=Age-related patterns of reproductive success in house sparrows ''Passer domesticus'' |last1=Hatch|first1=Margret I.|first2=David F. |last2=Westneat|doi=10.1111/j.0908-8857.2007.04044.x |bibcode=2007JAvBi..38..603H }}</ref> As the breeding season approaches, hormone releases trigger enormous increases in the size of the [[sexual organs]] and changes in day length lead males to start calling by nesting sites.<ref>{{Cite journal
| last1 = Whitfield-Rucker | first1 = M.
| last2 = Cassone | first2 = V. M.
| doi = 10.1006/gcen.2000.7455
| title = Photoperiodic Regulation of the Male House Sparrow Song Control System: Gonadal Dependent and Independent Mechanisms
| journal = General and Comparative Endocrinology
| volume = 118
| issue = 1
| pages = 173–183
| year = 2000
| pmid = 10753579}}</ref>{{sfn|Birkhead|2012|pp=47–48}} The timing of mating and egg-laying varies geographically, and between specific locations and years because a sufficient supply of insects is needed for egg formation and feeding nestlings.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=144–147}}

Males take up nesting sites before the breeding season, by frequently calling beside them. Unmated males start nest construction and call particularly frequently to attract females. When a female approaches a male during this period, the male [[courtship display|displays]] by moving up and down while drooping and shivering his wings, pushing up his head, raising and spreading his tail, and showing his bib.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=144–147}} Males may try to mate with females while calling or displaying. In response, a female will adopt a threatening posture and attack a male before flying away, pursued by the male. The male displays in front of her, attracting other males, which also pursue and display to the female. This group display usually does not immediately result in copulations.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=144–147}} Other males usually do not copulate with the female.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=142–143}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Brackbill|first=Hervey|title=Two Male House Sparrows Copulating on Ground with Same Female|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v086n01/p0146-p0146.pdf|journal=The Auk|year=1969|volume=86|issue=1|doi=10.2307/4083563|page=146|jstor=4083563}}</ref> Copulation is typically initiated by the female giving a soft ''dee-dee-dee'' call to the male. Birds of a pair [[copulation (zoology)|copulate]] frequently until the female is laying eggs, and the male mounts the female repeatedly each time a pair mates.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=144–147}}

The house sparrow is [[Monogamy in animals|monogamous]], and typically mates for life, but birds from pairs often engage in [[extra-pair copulation]]s, so about 15% of house sparrow fledglings are unrelated to their mother's mate.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=141–142}} Males guard their mates carefully to avoid being cuckolded, and most extra-pair copulation occurs away from nest sites.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=142–143}}{{sfn|Anderson|2006|p=145}} Males may sometimes have multiple mates, and bigamy is mostly limited by aggression between females.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=143–144}} Many birds do not find a nest and a mate, and instead may serve as [[helpers at the nest|helpers]] around the nest for mated pairs, a role which increases the chances of being chosen to replace a lost mate. Lost mates of both sexes can be replaced quickly during the breeding season.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=142–143}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Anderson|first=T. R.|contribution=Excess females in a breeding population of House Sparrows [''Passer domesticus'' (L.)]|pages=87–94|title=Granivorous birds in the agricultural landscape|editor=Pinowski, J. |editor2=Summers-Smith, J. D.|year=1990|publisher=Pánstwowe Wydawnictom Naukowe|location=Warszawa|isbn=978-83-01-08460-8}}</ref> The formation of a pair and the bond between the two birds is tied to the holding of a nest site, though paired house sparrows can recognise each other away from the nest.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=144–147}}

House sparrows in natural small populations, as can occur on islands, exhibit [[inbreeding depression]].<ref name="Billing2012">{{cite journal |vauthors=Billing AM, Lee AM, Skjelseth S, Borg AA, Hale MC, Slate J, Pärn H, Ringsby TH, Saether BE, Jensen H |title=Evidence of inbreeding depression but not inbreeding avoidance in a natural house sparrow population |journal=Mol Ecol |volume=21 |issue=6 |pages=1487–99 |date=March 2012 |pmid=22335620 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-294X.2012.05490.x |bibcode=2012MolEc..21.1487B }}</ref><ref name="Niskanen2020">{{cite journal |vauthors=Niskanen AK, Billing AM, Holand H, Hagen IJ, Araya-Ajoy YG, Husby A, Rønning B, Myhre AM, Ranke PS, Kvalnes T, Pärn H, Ringsby TH, Lien S, Sæther BE, Muff S, Jensen H |title=Consistent scaling of inbreeding depression in space and time in a house sparrow metapopulation |journal=Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A |volume=117 |issue=25 |pages=14584–92 |date=June 2020 |pmid=32513746 |pmc=7322018 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1909599117 |doi-access=free |bibcode=2020PNAS..11714584N }}</ref>  Inbreeding depression is manifested as lower survival probability and production of fewer offspring, and can occur as a result of the expression of deleterious recessive [[allele]]s.<ref name = Niskanen2020/> In such populations sparrows do not appear to [[inbreeding avoidance|avoid inbreeding]].<ref name = Billing2012/>

====Nesting====
[[File:Passer domesticus -with an insect for her young -female -nest-8b.jpg|thumb|Female bringing food for young in a nest made in a tree hole in [[California]]]]
[[File:Sparrow in a ventilator.jpg|alt=Sparrow in a ventilator|thumb|An example of a nest made in a man-made structure.]]
Nest sites are varied, though cavities are preferred. Nests are most frequently built in the [[eaves]] and other crevices of houses. Holes in cliffs and banks, and [[tree hollow]]s, are also used.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=52–57}}<ref name=Indykiewicz/> A sparrow sometimes excavates its own nests in sandy banks or rotten branches, but more frequently uses the nests of other birds such as those of [[swallow]]s in banks and cliffs, and old tree cavity nests. It usually uses deserted nests, though sometimes it usurps active ones by driving away or killing the occupants.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=52–57}}<ref name=Gowaty>{{Cite journal|last=Gowaty|first=Patricia Adair|title=House Sparrows Kill Eastern Bluebirds|journal=Journal of Field Ornithology|volume= 55|issue=3|pages=378–380|date=Summer 1984|url =http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/jfo/v055n03/p0378-p0380.pdf |access-date=1 October 2009}}</ref> Tree hollows are more commonly used in North America than in Europe,{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=52–57}} putting the sparrows in competition with [[bluebird]]s and other North American cavity nesters, and thereby contributing to their population declines.<ref name=scapegoat/>

Especially in warmer areas, the house sparrow may build its nests in the open, on the branches of trees, especially evergreens and hawthorns, or in the nests of large birds such as [[stork]]s or [[magpie]]s.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=144–147}}{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=52–57}}{{sfn|Haverschmidt|1949|pp=33–34}} In open nesting sites, breeding success tends to be lower, since breeding begins late and the nest can easily be destroyed or damaged by storms.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=52–57}}{{sfn|Morris|Tegetmeier|1896|pp=8–9}} Less common nesting sites include [[street light]]s and [[neon sign]]s, favoured for their warmth; and the old open-topped nests of other songbirds, which are then domed over.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=52–57}}<ref name=Indykiewicz/>
Usually the couples repeat copulation many times. Every copulation is followed by some break of 3 to 4 seconds, and in that time both pair change their position by some distance.
The nest is usually domed, though it may lack a roof in enclosed sites.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=52–57}} It has an outer layer of stems and roots, a middle layer of dead grass and leaves, and a lining of feathers, as well as of paper and other soft materials.<ref name=Indykiewicz>{{cite book|last=Indykiewicz|first=Piotr|contribution=Nest-sites and nests of House Sparrow [''Passer domesticus'' (L.)] in an urban environment|pages=95–121|title=Granivorous birds in the agricultural landscape|editor=Pinowski, J. |editor2=Summers-Smith, J. D.|year=1990|publisher=Pánstwowe Wydawnictom Naukowe|location=Warszawa|isbn=978-83-01-08460-8}}</ref> Nests typically have external dimensions of 20 × 30&nbsp;cm (8 × 12&nbsp;in),{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=144–147}} but their size varies greatly.<ref name=Indykiewicz/> The building of the nest is initiated by the unmated male while displaying to females. The female assists in building, but is less active than the male.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=52–57}} Some nest building occurs throughout the year, especially after moult in autumn. In colder areas house sparrows build specially created roost nests, or roost in street lights, to avoid losing heat during the winter.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=52–57}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Jansen|first=R. R.|title=House Sparrows build roost nests|journal=The Loon|volume=55|pages=64–65|year=1983|issn=0024-645X|url=http://moumn.org/loon/view_frame.php?page=64&year=1983}}</ref> House sparrows do not hold territories, but they defend their nests aggressively against intruders of the same sex.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=52–57}}

House sparrows' nests support a wide range of scavenging insects, including nest flies such as ''[[Neottiophilum praestum]]'', ''[[Protocalliphora]]'' blowflies,{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963| pp=131–132}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturespot.org.uk/species/neottiophilum-praeustum|title=''Neottiophilum praeustum''|work=NatureSpot|access-date=10 January 2012}}</ref> and over 1,400 species of beetle.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Sustek |first=Zbyšek |author2=Hokntchova, Daša |year=1983 |title=The beetles (Coleoptera) in the nests of ''Delichon urbica'' in Slovakia |journal=Acta Rerum Naturalium Musei Nationalis Slovaci, Bratislava |volume=XXIX |pages=119–134 |url=http://akademickyrepozitar.sk/sk/repozitar/the-beetles-coleoptera-in-the-nests-of-dolichon-urbica-in-slovakia.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328105719/http://akademickyrepozitar.sk/sk/repozitar/the-beetles-coleoptera-in-the-nests-of-dolichon-urbica-in-slovakia.pdf |archive-date=28 March 2012  }}</ref>

====Eggs and young====
[[File:Passerdomesticuseggs.JPG|thumb|left|Eggs in a nest]]
[[Clutch (eggs)|Clutches]] usually comprise four or five [[Bird egg|eggs]], though numbers from one to 10 have been recorded. At least two clutches are usually laid, and up to seven a year may be laid in the tropics or four a year in temperate latitudes. When fewer clutches are laid in a year, especially at higher latitudes, the number of eggs per clutch is greater. Central Asian house sparrows, which migrate and have only one clutch a year, average 6.5&nbsp;eggs in a clutch. Clutch size is also affected by environmental and seasonal conditions, female age, and breeding density.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=148–149}}{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=157–172}}

[[File:House sparrow chick.jpg|thumb|alt=Naked and blind chick|A hatchling with yellow [[Beak#Gape|gape]]]]

Some intraspecific [[brood parasite|brood parasitism]] occurs, and instances of unusually large numbers of eggs in a nest may be the result of females laying eggs in the nests of their neighbours. Such foreign eggs are sometimes recognised and ejected by females.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=148–149}}{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=145–146}} The house sparrow is a victim of interspecific brood parasites, but only rarely, since it usually uses nests in holes too small for parasites to enter, and it feeds its young foods unsuitable for young parasites.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|p=319}}{{sfn|Davies|2000|p=55}} In turn, the house sparrow has once been recorded as a brood parasite of the [[American cliff swallow]].{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=145–146}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Stoner|first=Dayton|title=Parasitism of the English Sparrow on the Northern Cliff Swallow|date=December 1939|journal=Wilson Bulletin|volume=51|issue=4|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v051n04/p0221-p0222.pdf}}</ref>

[[File:House sparrow portrait.jpg|thumb|left|A juvenile, showing its pink bill and obvious nestling [[gape]]—the soft, swollen base, which becomes harder and less swollen as the bird matures]]
The eggs are white, bluish white, or greenish white, spotted with brown or grey.<ref name=Poole>{{cite web|last1=Lowther|first1=Peter E.|last2=Cink|first2=Calvin L.|year=2006|title=House Sparrow (''Passer domesticus'')|work=The Birds of North America Online|editor=Poole, A.|url=https://bna.birds.cornell.edu/bna/species/012|access-date=21 April 2010}}</ref> Subelliptical in shape,<ref name=Groschupf/> they range from {{convert|20 to 22|mm|abbr=on}} in length and {{convert|14 to 16|mm|abbr=on}} in width,<ref name="all about"/> have an average mass of {{convert|2.9|g|oz|abbr=on}},<ref name=BTO>{{cite web|url=http://blx1.bto.org/birdfacts/results/bob15910.htm|title=BTO Bird facts: House Sparrow|access-date=24 November 2009|publisher=British Trust for Ornithology}}</ref> and an average surface area of {{convert|9.18|cm2|in2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=Paganelli>{{cite journal|doi=10.2307/1366345|last=Paganelli|first=C. V. |author2=Olszowka, A. |author3=Ali, A.|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v076n03/p0319-p0325.pdf|title=The Avian Egg: Surface Area, Volume, and Density|journal=The Condor|year=1974|volume=76|pages=319–325|issue=3|jstor=1366345 |bibcode=1974Condo..76..319P }}</ref> Eggs from the tropical subspecies are distinctly smaller.{{sfn|Ogilvie-Grant|1912|pp=201–204}}{{sfn|Hume|Oates|1890|pp=169–151}} Eggs begin to develop with the deposition of [[Egg yolk|yolk]] in the ovary a few days before ovulation. In the day between ovulation and laying, [[egg white]] forms, followed by [[eggshell]].{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=175–176}} Eggs laid later in a clutch are larger, as are those laid by larger females, and egg size is hereditary. Eggs decrease slightly in size from laying to hatching.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=173–175}} The yolk comprises 25% of the egg, the egg white 68%, and the shell 7%. Eggs are watery, being 79% liquid, and otherwise mostly protein.{{sfn|Anderson|2006| pp=176–177}}

The female develops a [[brood patch]] of bare skin and plays the main part in [[avian incubation|incubating]] the eggs. The male helps, but can only cover the eggs rather than truly incubate them. The female spends the night incubating during this period, while the male roosts near the nest.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=148–149}} Eggs hatch at the same time, after a short incubation period lasting 11–14&nbsp;days, and exceptionally for as many as 17 or as few as 9.<ref name=Groschupf>{{cite book|year=2001|contribution=Old World Sparrows|title=The Sibley Guide to Bird Life and Behaviour |publisher=Christopher Helm|location=London |first=Kathleen |last=Groschupf|pages=562–4|isbn=978-0-7136-6250-4 |editor1=Elphick, Chris |editor2=Dunning, John B. Jr. |editor3=Sibley, David }}</ref>{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=144–147}}<ref>{{cite journal|author-link=Margaret Morse Nice|last=Nice|first=Margaret Morse|title=The Question of Ten-day Incubation Periods|year=1953|journal=The Wilson Bulletin|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v065n02/p0081-p0093.pdf|issue=2|volume=65|pages=81–93}}</ref> The length of the incubation period decreases as ambient temperature increases later in the breeding season.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=149–150}}

Young house sparrows remain in the nest for 11 to 23 days, normally 14 to 16 days.<ref name=Poole/>{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=149–150}}{{sfn|Glutz von Blotzheim|Bauer|1997|p=60ff}} During this time, they are fed by both parents. As newly hatched house sparrows do not have sufficient insulation, they are brooded for a few days, or longer in cold conditions.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=149–150}}{{sfn|Glutz von Blotzheim|Bauer|1997|pp=105–115}} The parents swallow the droppings produced by the hatchlings during the first few days; later, the droppings are moved up to {{convert|20|m|ft|abbr=on}} away from the nest.{{sfn|Glutz von Blotzheim|Bauer|1997|pp=105–115}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nature-rings.de/tiere/36/page1.html |publisher=nature-rings.de|title=Der es von den Dächern pfeift: Der Haussperling (''Passer domesticus'')|language=de}}</ref>

The chicks' eyes open after about 4 days and, at an age of about 8 days, the young birds get their first [[down feather|down]].<ref name=Poole/>{{sfn|Glutz von Blotzheim|Bauer|1997|p=60ff}} If both parents perish, the ensuing intensive begging sounds of the young often attract replacement parents which feed them until they can sustain themselves.{{sfn|Glutz von Blotzheim|Bauer|1997|pp=105–115}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.giebing.de/sperling.htm|first= Manfred |last=Giebing|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071122110201/http://www.giebing.de/sperling.htm|archive-date=22 November 2007|title=Der Haussperling: Vogel des Jahres 2002|date=31 October 2006|language=de}}</ref> All the young in the nest leave it during the same period of a few hours. At this stage, they are normally able to fly. They start feeding themselves partly after 1 or 2 days, and sustain themselves completely after 7 to 10 days, 14 at the latest.{{sfn|Glutz von Blotzheim|Bauer|1997|pp=79–89}}

==Survival==
In adult house sparrows, annual survival is 45–65%.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=154–155}} After fledging and leaving the care of their parents, young sparrows have a high mortality rate, which lessens as they grow older and more experienced. Only about 20–25% of birds hatched survive to their first breeding season.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=137–141}} The oldest known wild house sparrow lived for nearly two decades; it was found dead 19&nbsp;years and 9&nbsp;months after it was [[bird ringing|ringed]] in Denmark.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euring.org/data_and_codes/longevity-voous.htm|access-date=24 November 2009|publisher=EURING: The European Union for Bird Ringing|title=European Longevity Records}}</ref> The oldest recorded captive house sparrow lived for 23&nbsp;years.<ref>{{cite web|title=AnAge entry for ''Passer domesticus''|url=http://genomics.senescence.info/species/entry.php?species=Passer_domesticus|access-date=1 February 2010|work=AnAge: the Animal Ageing and Longevity Database}}</ref> The typical ratio of males to females in a population is uncertain due to problems in collecting data, but a very slight preponderance of males at all ages is usual.{{sfn|Anderson|2006| pp=333–336}}

===Predation===
[[File:Cat-eating-prey.jpg|thumb|A male sparrow being eaten by a [[Cat|domestic cat]]. Cats are one of the main predators of the house sparrow.]]
The house sparrow's main predators are [[cat]]s and [[Bird of prey|birds of prey]], but many other animals prey on them, including [[Corvidae|corvids]], [[squirrel]]s,{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=304–306}} and even humans—the house sparrow has been consumed in the past by people in many parts of the world, and it still is in parts of the Mediterranean.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1992|pp=30–33}} Most species of birds of prey have been recorded preying on the house sparrow in places where records are extensive. [[Accipiter]]s and the [[Merlin (bird)|merlin]] in particular are major predators, though cats are likely to have a greater impact on house sparrow populations.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=304–306}} The house sparrow is also a common victim of [[roadkill]]; on European roads, it is the bird most frequently found dead.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Erritzoe|first1= J.|last2=Mazgajski|first2=T. D.|last3= Rejt|first3=L.|year=2003|url=http://www.birdresearch.dk/unilang/articles/traffic.pdf|title=Bird casualties on European roads – a review|journal=Acta Ornithologica|volume=38|issue=2|pages=77–93|doi=10.3161/068.038.0204|s2cid= 52832425|doi-access=free}}</ref>

===Parasites and disease===
The house sparrow is host to a huge number of parasites and diseases, and the effect of most is unknown. Ornithologist Ted R. Anderson listed thousands, noting that his list was incomplete.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=311–317}} The commonly recorded bacterial pathogens of the house sparrow are often those common in humans, and include ''[[Salmonella]]'' and ''[[Escherichia coli]]''.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|p=128}} ''Salmonella'' is common in the house sparrow, and a comprehensive study of house sparrow disease found it in 13% of sparrows tested. ''Salmonella'' epidemics in the spring and winter can kill large numbers of sparrows.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=311–317}} The house sparrow hosts [[avian pox]] and [[avian malaria]], which it has spread to the native forest birds of Hawaii.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=van Riper|first1=Charles III|first2=Sandra G.|last2=van Riper|first3=Wallace R.|last3=Hansen|journal=The Auk|volume=119|issue=4|pages=929–942|year=2002|title=Epizootiology and Effect of Avian Pox on Hawaiian Forest Birds|doi=10.1642/0004-8038(2002)119[0929:EAEOAP]2.0.CO;2|s2cid=449004 |issn=0004-8038|doi-access=free}}</ref> Many of the diseases hosted by the house sparrow are also present in humans and domestic animals, for which the house sparrow acts as a [[natural reservoir|reservoir host]].{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=427–429}} [[Arbovirus infection|Arboviruses]] such as the [[West Nile virus]], which most commonly infect insects and mammals, survive winters in temperate areas by going dormant in birds such as the house sparrow.{{sfn|Anderson|2006|pp=311–317}}<ref>{{cite journal|date=1 November 2000|title=Sparrow suspect|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn122-sparrow-suspect.html|journal=New Scientist|access-date=25 May 2010|last=Young|first=Emma}}</ref> A few records indicate disease extirpating house sparrow populations, especially from Scottish islands, but this seems to be rare.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|p=129}} House sparrows are also infected by [[Haemosporida|haemosporidian]] parasites, but less so in urban than in rural areas<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Santiago-Alarcon|first1=Diego|last2=Carbó-Ramírez|first2=Pilar|last3=Macgregor-Fors|first3=Ian|last4=Chávez-Zichinelli|first4=Carlos Alberto|last5=Yeh|first5=Pamela J.|date=2020|title=The prevalence of avian haemosporidian parasites in an invasive bird is lower in urban than in non-urban environments|journal=Ibis|language=en|volume=162|issue=1|pages=201–214|doi=10.1111/ibi.12699|s2cid=91994621|issn=1474-919X}}</ref> ''[[Toxoplasma gondii]]'' has been detected in sparrows in northwestern China where they pose a risk due to their meat being consumed in the region.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Cong|first1=Wei|last2=Huang|first2=Si-Yang|last3=Zhou|first3=Dong-Hui|last4=Zhang|first4=Xiao-Xuan|last5=Zhang|first5=Nian-Zhang|last6=Zhao|first6=Quan|last7=Zhu|first7=Xing-Quan|date=2013|title=Prevalence and Genetic Characterization of ''Toxoplasma gondii'' in House Sparrows (''Passer domesticus'') in Lanzhou, China|journal=The Korean Journal of Parasitology|volume=51|issue=3|pages=363–7|doi=10.3347/kjp.2013.51.3.363|issn=0023-4001|pmc=3712113|pmid=23864750}}</ref>

The house sparrow is infested by a number of external parasites, which usually cause little harm to adult sparrows. In Europe, the most common [[mite]] found on sparrows is ''[[Proctophyllodes]]'', the most common [[tick]]s are ''[[Argas reflexus]]'' and ''[[Ixodes arboricola]]'', and the most common flea on the house sparrow is ''[[Ceratophyllus gallinae]]''.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963| pp=131–132}} ''[[Dermanyssus]]'' blood-feeding mites are also common ectoparasites of house sparrows,<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Poiani|first1=A.|last2=Goldsmith|first2=A. R.|last3=Evans|first3=M. R.|date=2000-03-23|title=Ectoparasites of house sparrows (''Passer domesticus''): an experimental test of the immunocompetence handicap hypothesis and a new model|journal=Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology|language=en|volume=47|issue=4|pages=230–242|doi=10.1007/s002650050660|bibcode=2000BEcoS..47..230P |s2cid=5913876|issn=0340-5443}}</ref> and these mites can enter human habitation and bite humans, causing a condition known as [[gamasoidosis]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Neill|first1=S. M.|last2=Monk|first2=B. E.|last3=Pembroke|first3=A.C.|date=1985|title=Gamasoidosis: avian mite dermatitis (Dermanyssus gallinae)|journal=British Journal of Dermatology|language=en|volume=113|issue=s29|page=44|doi=10.1111/j.1365-2133.1985.tb13013.x|s2cid=84993822|issn=0007-0963}}</ref> A number of [[chewing louse|chewing lice]] occupy different [[Ecological niche|niches]] on the house sparrow's body. ''[[Menacanthus]]'' lice occur across the house sparrow's body, where they feed on blood and feathers, while ''[[Brueelia]]'' lice feed on feathers and ''[[Philopterus fringillae]]'' occurs on the head.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963| pp=131–132}}

==Physiology==
House sparrows express strong [[circadian rhythm]]s of activity in the laboratory. They were among the first bird species to be seriously studied in terms of their circadian activity and [[photoperiodism]], in part because of their availability and adaptability in captivity, but also because they can "find their way" and remain rhythmic in constant darkness.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Menaker|first=M.|year=1972|title=Nonvisual light reception|journal=Scientific American|volume= 226|issue=3|pages=22–29|bibcode=1972SciAm.226c..22M|doi=10.1038/scientificamerican0372-22|pmid=5062027}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Sue Binkley |last=Tatem |title=The clockwork sparrow: Time, clocks, and calendars in biological organisms |publisher=Prentice Hall |location= |date=1990 |isbn=0-13-073701-1 |oclc=681290505 }}</ref>

==Relationships with humans==
[[File:Passer domesticus - gathering at fluorescent tube.ogv|thumb|Flocking and chirping together beneath a [[fluorescent tube]] light in Germany]]
The house sparrow is closely associated with humans. They are believed to have become associated with humans around 10,000 years ago. The Turkestan subspecies (''P.&nbsp;d. bactrianus'') is least associated with humans and considered to be evolutionarily closer to the ancestral noncommensal populations.<ref>{{cite journal|doi= 10.1111/j.1420-9101.2012.02470.x | title= Single origin of human commensalism in the house sparrow|journal=Journal of Evolutionary Biology|volume=25|issue=4|year=2012| pages=788–796|last1=Sætre|first1=G.-P. |last2=Riyahi |first2=S. |last3=Alibadian |first3=M. |last4=Hermansen |first4=J.S. |last5=Hogner |first5=S. |last6=Olsson |first6=U. |last7=Rojas |first7=M.F.G. |last8=Sæther |first8=S.A. |last9=Trier |first9=C.N. |last10=Elgvin |first10=T.O.|pmid= 22320215 | s2cid= 11011958|display-authors=1| bibcode= 2012JEBio..25..788S|doi-access=free}}</ref> Usually, the house sparrow is regarded as a pest, since it consumes agricultural products and spreads disease to humans and their domestic animals.{{sfn|Anderson|2006| pp=425–429}} Even [[Birdwatching|birdwatchers]] often hold it in little regard because of its molestation of other birds.<ref name="scapegoat"/> In most of the world, the house sparrow is not protected by law. Attempts to control house sparrows include the trapping, poisoning, or shooting of adults; the destruction of their nests and eggs; or less directly, blocking nest holes and scaring off sparrows with noise, glue, or porcupine wire.<ref name=ISSG>{{cite web|url=http://www.issg.org/database/species/ecology.asp?fr=1&si=420&lang=EN|title=ISSG Database: Ecology of ''Passer domesticus''|author=Invasive Species Specialist Group|access-date=16 January 2009|archive-date=11 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611203540/http://www.issg.org/database/species/ecology.asp?fr=1&si=420&lang=EN}}</ref> However, the house sparrow can be beneficial to humans, as well, especially by eating insect pests, and attempts at the large-scale control of the house sparrow have failed.<ref name=HBW/>

The house sparrow has long been used as a food item. From around 1560 to at least the 19th century in northern Europe, [[earthenware]] "sparrow pots" were hung from eaves to attract nesting birds so the young could be readily harvested. Wild birds were trapped in nets in large numbers, and sparrow pie was a traditional dish, thought, because of the association of sparrows with [[Lascivious#Lechery|lechery]], to have [[aphrodisiac]] properties.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|2005|pp= 29–35}} A traditional Indian medicine, ''Ciṭṭukkuruvi [[Lehyam|lēkiyam]]'' in [[Tamil language|Tamil]], was sold with similar aphrodisiac claims.<ref>{{cite report|author=Susainathan, P.|author-link=P.S. Nathan|year=1921|title=Bird friends and foes of the farmer. Bulletin No. 81|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.219743/page/n38/mode/1up|publisher=Department of Agriculture|page=22|place=Madras}}</ref> Sparrows were also trapped as food for [[falconry|falconers']] birds and zoo animals. During the 1870s, there were debates on the damaging effects of sparrows in the House of Commons in England.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Holmes|first=Matthew|date=2017-08-01|title=The Sparrow Question: Social and Scientific Accord in Britain, 1850–1900|journal=Journal of the History of Biology|language=en|volume=50|issue=3|pages=645–671|doi=10.1007/s10739-016-9455-6|pmid=27785658|issn=1573-0387|doi-access=free}}</ref> In the early part of the 20th century, sparrow clubs culled many millions of birds and eggs in an attempt to control numbers of this perceived pest, but with only a localised impact on numbers.{{sfn|Cocker|Mabey|2005|pp=436–443}} Sparrows were also persecuted in Germany from at least 1650 until 1970.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Seitz |first=J. |date=2007 |title=Three hundred years of House Sparrow (Passer domesticus) persecution in Germany |journal=Archives of Natural History |volume=34 |issue=2 |pages=307–317 |doi=10.3366/anh.2007.34.2.307 |issn=0260-9541}}</ref> House sparrows have been kept as pets at many times in history, though they have no bright plumage or attractive songs, and raising them is difficult.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|2005|pp= 29–35}} The house sparrow has an extremely large range and population, so it is assessed as [[least concern]] for conservation on the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=IUCN />

==Population decline==
The [[IUCN]] estimates for the global population runs up to nearly 1.4 billion individuals, second among all wild birds perhaps only to the [[red-billed quelea]] in abundance (although the quelea is, unlike the sparrow, restricted to a single continent and has never been subject to human introductions).<ref name=IUCN /> However, populations have been declining in many parts of the world, especially near its Eurasian places of origin.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2005-06-13/delhi/27852762_1_house-sparrow-birds-crows |title=Even sparrows don't want to live in cities anymore |date=13 June 2005 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811025910/http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2005-06-13/delhi/27852762_1_house-sparrow-birds-crows |archive-date=11 August 2011  |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Daniels, R. J. Ranjit |year=2008 |title=Can we save the sparrow? |journal=Current Science |volume=95 |issue=11 |pages=1527–8 |url=http://www.ias.ac.in/currsci/dec102008/1527.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623000716/http://www.ias.ac.in/currsci/dec102008/1527.pdf |archive-date=23 June 2017  }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=De Laet, J. |author2=Summers-Smith, J. D. |year=2007|title=The status of the urban house sparrow ''Passer domesticus'' in northwestern Europe: a review|journal=Journal of Ornithology|volume=148|issue=Supplement 2|doi=10.1007/s10336-007-0154-0|pages=275–8|bibcode=2007JOrn..148..275D |s2cid=10987859 }}</ref> These declines were first noticed in North America, where they were initially attributed to the spread of the [[house finch]], but have been most severe in [[Western Europe]].{{sfn|Anderson|2006 | p=320}}<ref>{{cite journal |author=Summers-Smith, J. Denis |title=Changes in the House Sparrow Population in Britain |url=https://www.wnb.uz.zgora.pl/assets/files/iss/iss_vol30_03.pdf |year=2005 |journal=International Studies on Sparrows |volume=5 |pages=23–37 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307044158/https://www.wnb.uz.zgora.pl/assets/files/iss/iss_vol30_03.pdf |archive-date=7 March 2012  }}</ref> Declines have even occurred in Australia, where the house sparrow was introduced recently.{{sfn|Anderson|2006| pp=229–300}} While no serious declines had been reported from [[Eastern Europe]] by 2006,{{sfn|Anderson|2006| pp=229–300}} as of 2023, a 50% decrease of the sparrow population has been registered in [[Bulgaria]].<ref name=bnr>[https://bnr.bg/radiobulgaria/post/101835143/drastichno-namalava-broat-na-vrabchetata-trevojen-znak-za-problem-v-prirodata Драстично намалява броят на врабчетата – тревожен знак за проблем в природата. Българско национално радио. 11.06.23]</ref>

In Europe, citizen science data from a 21-year study found its numbers had dwindled in its native range in Europe by nearly 60% by 2021.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2021-02-11 |title=Study finds even the common House Sparrow is declining {{!}} CALS |url=https://cals.cornell.edu/news/2021/02/study-finds-even-common-house-sparrow-declining |access-date=2024-10-20 |website=cals.cornell.edu |language=en}}</ref> In [[Great Britain]], populations peaked in the early 1970s,{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=157–158, 296}} but have since declined by 68% overall,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/7738798.stm|title=Sparrow numbers 'plummet by 68%'|date=20 November 2008 |publisher=BBC News|access-date=6 December 2009}}</ref> and about 90% in some regions.<ref name=McCarthy>{{cite news|last=McCarthy|first=Michael|title=It was once a common or garden bird. Now it's not common or in your garden. Why?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/it-was-once-a-common-or-garden-bird-now-its-not-common-or-in-your-garden-why-718073.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606090440/http://www.independent.co.uk/environment/it-was-once-a-common-or-garden-bird-now-its-not-common-or-in-your-garden-why-718073.html|archive-date=6 June 2011|newspaper=The Independent|date=16 May 2000|access-date=12 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arkive.org/house-sparrow/passer-domesticus/|title=House sparrow|work=[[ARKive]]|access-date=27 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110703204708/http://www.arkive.org/house-sparrow/passer-domesticus/|archive-date=3 July 2011}}</ref> The RSPB lists the house sparrow's UK conservation status as red.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rspb.org.uk/birds-and-wildlife/wildlife-guides/bird-a-z/house-sparrow|title=House sparrow|work=[[RSPB]]|access-date=25 January 2019}}</ref> In London, the house sparrow almost disappeared from the central city.<ref name=McCarthy/> The numbers of house sparrows in the [[Netherlands]] have dropped in half since the 1980s,<ref name="Poel">{{cite web|last=van der Poel|first=Guus|date=29 January 2001|url=http://www.xs4all.nl/~amvdpoel/Home.htm|title=Concerns about the population decline of the House Sparrow ''Passer domesticus'' in the Netherlands|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050213082856/http://www.xs4all.nl/~amvdpoel/Home.htm|archive-date=13 February 2005}}</ref> so the house sparrow is even considered an [[endangered species]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Gould|first=Anne Blair|title=House sparrow dwindling|publisher=Radio Nederland Wereldomroep|date=29 November 2004| url=http://www2.rnw.nl/rnw/en/features/science/041129rf| archive-url=https://archive.today/20051127075716/http://www2.rnw.nl/rnw/en/features/science/041129rf| archive-date=27 November 2005}}</ref> This status came to widespread attention after a female house sparrow, referred to as the "[[Domino Day 2005 sparrow|dominomus]]", was killed after knocking down dominoes arranged as part of an attempt to set a world record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4450958.stm|title=Sparrow death mars record attempt|date=19 November 2005 |publisher=BBC News|access-date=10 August 2011}}</ref> These declines are not unprecedented, as similar reductions in population occurred when the internal combustion engine replaced horses in the 1920s and a major source of food in the form of grain spillage was lost.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1988|p=156}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Bergtold|first=W. H.|date=April 1921|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v038n02/p0244-p0250.pdf|title=The English Sparrow (''Passer domesticus'') and the Automobile|journal=The Auk|volume=38|issue=2|pages=244–250|doi=10.2307/4073887|jstor=4073887}}</ref>

Declines have been particularly apparent even in North America, where the house sparrow is invasive in some states. Introduced to Philadelphia initially in 1852 the house sparrow rapidly spread across the nation. However, the bird has largely disappeared from the city nowadays and is estimated to have declined in North America by 84% since 1966.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://blog.nature.org/science/2019/03/25/where-have-all-the-house-sparrows-gone/amp/ |title= where have all the house sparrows gone?=6 October 2022 |work= blog.nature |date= 25 March 2019 |access-date= 6 October 2022 |archive-date= 6 October 2022 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20221006034046/https://blog.nature.org/science/2019/03/25/where-have-all-the-house-sparrows-gone/amp/ }}</ref>

In [[South Asia]], the house sparrow has largely vanished from many major cities.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.aa.com.tr/en/environment/sparrows-disappearing-from-skies-of-south-asian-metropolises/2540015 | title=sparrows disappearing from the skies of south Asian metropolises=6 October 2022|work=AA}}</ref> In general, the house sparrow population has been on the decline in many Asian countries, particularly in India.<ref name="The Hindu-2013" /> 

Various causes for the dramatic decreases in population have been proposed, including predation, in particular by [[Eurasian sparrowhawk]]s,<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Ross|last=MacLeod |author2=Barnett, Phil |author3=Clark, Jacquie |author4=Cresswell, Will|title=Mass-dependent predation risk as a mechanism for house sparrow declines?|doi=10.1098/rsbl.2005.0421|journal=Biology Letters|volume=2|issue=1|pages=43–46|date=23 March 2006|pmid=17148322|pmc=1617206 |bibcode=2006BiLet...2...43M }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Auk|volume=127|issue=2|pages=411–420|year=2010|doi=10.1525/auk.2009.09108|title=The Role of the Eurasian Sparrowhawk (''Accipiter nisus'') in the Decline of the House Sparrow (''Passer domesticus'') in Britain|first1=Christopher P.|last1=Bell|first2=Sam W.|last2=Baker|last3=Parkes|last4=Brooke|first5=Dan E.|last5=Chamberlain|first3=Nigel G.|first4=M. de L.|bibcode=2010Auk...127..411B |s2cid=86228079|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=McCarthy3>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/nature/mystery-of-the-vanishing-sparrows-still-baffles-scientists-10-years-on-2056309.html|title=Mystery of the vanishing sparrows still baffles scientists 10 years on |date=19 August 2010|last=McCarthy|first=Michael|newspaper=The Independent|access-date=24 September 2011}}</ref> possibly facilitated by the elimination of bushes which the sparrows use to hide,<ref name=bnr/> electromagnetic radiation from mobile phones;<ref>{{Cite journal|first1=Alfonso|last1=Balmori|first2=Örjan|last2=Hallberg|title=The Urban Decline of the House Sparrow (''Passer domesticus''): A Possible Link with Electromagnetic Radiation |journal=[[Electromagnetic Biology and Medicine]]|volume=26|issue=2|pages=141–151|doi=10.1080/15368370701410558 |year=2007|pmid=17613041|s2cid=2936866}}</ref> and diseases<ref name=McCarthy2/> such as avian malaria.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Dadam|first1=Daria|last2=Robinson|first2=Robert A.|last3=Clements|first3=Anabel|last4=Peach|first4=Will J.|last5=Bennett|first5=Malcolm|last6=Rowcliffe|first6=J. Marcus|last7=Cunningham|first7=Andrew A.|date=2019-07-26|title=Avian malaria-mediated population decline of a widespread iconic bird species|journal=Royal Society Open Science|language=en|volume=6|issue=7|article-number=182197|doi=10.1098/rsos.182197|doi-access=free|pmid=31417708|pmc=6689627|issn=2054-5703|bibcode=2019RSOS....682197D}}</ref> A shortage of nesting sites caused by changes in urban building design is probably a factor, and conservation organisations have encouraged the use of special nest boxes for sparrows.<ref name=McCarthy2>{{cite news|title=Mystery of the vanishing sparrow|last=McCarthy|first=Michael|date=20 November 2008|newspaper=The Independent|access-date=17 January 2009|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/nature/mystery-of-the-vanishing-sparrow-1026319.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite conference|last=Vincent|first=Kate|author2=Baker Shepherd Gillespie|year=2006|conference=Ecobuild exhibition|access-date=10 January 2010|format=PowerPoint presentation|url=http://www.housesparrow.org/the_provision_of_birds_in_buildings.ppt|title=The provision of birds in buildings; turning buildings into bird-friendly habitats|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726155112/http://www.housesparrow.org/the_provision_of_birds_in_buildings.ppt|archive-date=26 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=De Laet, Jenny |author2=Summers-Smith, Denis |author3=Mallord, John |year=2009 |title=Meeting on the Decline of the Urban House Sparrow ''Passer domesticus'': Newcastle 2009 (24–25 Feb) |url=http://iss.wnb.uz.zgora.pl/assets/files/prints/iss/iss_vol33.pdf |journal=International Studies on Sparrows |volume=33 |pages=17–32 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924000551/http://iss.wnb.uz.zgora.pl/assets/files/prints/iss/iss_vol33.pdf |archive-date=24 September 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/wildlife/4593534/Helping-birds-to-nest-on-Valentines-Day.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213190421/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/wildlife/4593534/Helping-birds-to-nest-on-Valentines-Day.html|archive-date=13 February 2009|title=Helping birds to nest on Valentine's Day|date=2 February 2009|author=Butler, Daniel|access-date=3 May 2010|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|location=London}}</ref> A primary cause of the decline seems to be an insufficient supply of insect food for nestling sparrows.<ref name=McCarthy2/><ref>{{cite journal|title=Reproductive success of house sparrows along an urban gradient|author1=Peach, W. J.|author2=Vincent, K. E.|author3=Fowler, J. A.|author4=Grice, P. V.|journal=Animal Conservation|url=http://www.housesparrow.org/reproductive_success_of_house_sparrows_along_an_urban_gradient.pdf|doi=10.1111/j.1469-1795.2008.00209.x|year=2008|volume=11|issue=6|pages=1–11|bibcode=2008AnCon..11..493P |s2cid=52366095 |access-date=18 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924031426/http://www.housesparrow.org/reproductive_success_of_house_sparrows_along_an_urban_gradient.pdf|archive-date=24 September 2015}}</ref> Declines in insect populations result from an increase of monoculture crops, the heavy use of pesticides,{{sfn|Vincent|2005|pp=265–270}}<ref>{{cite conference|author1=Vincent, Kate E.|author2=Peach, Will|author3=Fowler, Jim|conference=International Ornithological Congress|title=An investigation in to the breeding biology and nestling diet of the house sparrow in urban Britain|url=http://www.housesparrow.org/an_investigation_in_to_the_breeding_biology_and_nestling_diet_of_the_house_sparrow_in_urban_britain.ppt|format=PowerPoint presentation|year=2009|access-date=17 January 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726154841/http://www.housesparrow.org/an_investigation_in_to_the_breeding_biology_and_nestling_diet_of_the_house_sparrow_in_urban_britain.ppt|archive-date=26 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite conference|title=Reproductive success of house sparrows along an urban gradient|url=http://www.housesparrow.org/lipu_reproductive_success_of_house_sparrows_along_an_urban_gradient.ppt|format=PowerPoint presentation|year=2009|author=Vincent, Kate E.|conference=LIPU – Passeri in crisis?|location=Pisa, Italy|access-date=17 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110125042230/http://www.housesparrow.org/lipu_reproductive_success_of_house_sparrows_along_an_urban_gradient.ppt|archive-date=25 January 2011}}</ref> the replacement of native plants in cities with introduced plants and parking areas,<ref>{{cite news|author=Clover, Charles|date=20 November 2008|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/earthcomment/charlesclover/3491497/On-the-trail-of-our-missing-house-sparrows.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201084109/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/earthcomment/charlesclover/3491497/On-the-trail-of-our-missing-house-sparrows.html|archive-date=1 February 2009|title=On the trail of our missing house sparrows|newspaper=The Telegraph|location=London|access-date=25 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Smith, Lewis|title=Drivers and gardeners the secret behind flight of house sparrows|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/environment/article5192153.ece|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604150613/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/environment/article5192153.ece|archive-date=4 June 2011|newspaper=The Times|date=20 November 2008|access-date=17 January 2009}}</ref> and possibly the introduction of [[unleaded petrol]], which produces toxic compounds such as [[methyl nitrite]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Summers-Smith|first=J. Denis|journal=British Birds|volume=100|date=September 2007|page=558|issn=0007-0335|title=Is unleaded petrol a factor in urban House Sparrow decline?}}</ref>

Protecting insect habitats on farms<ref>{{cite web|title=Ecology and conservation of rural house sparrows|url=http://www.rspb.org.uk/ourwork/science/report/2002/ecology/ruralhousesparrows.asp|last=Hole|first=D. G. |author2=Whittingham, M. J. |author3=Bradbury, R. B. |author4=Anderson, G. Q. A. |author5=Lee, P. L. M. |author6=Wilson, J. D. |author7=Krebs, J. R.|year=2002|work=Ecology of Threatened Species|publisher=Royal Society for the Protection of Birds|access-date=17 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103062004/http://www.rspb.org.uk/ourwork/science/report/2002/ecology/ruralhousesparrows.asp|archive-date=3 January 2010 |display-authors=1}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=Nature|volume=418|pages=931–2|date=29 August 2002|doi=10.1038/418931a|title=Agriculture: Widespread local house-sparrow extinctions|first1=David G.|last1=Hole|first2=M. J.|last2=Whittingham|first3=Richard B.|last3=Bradbury|first4=Guy Q. A.|last4=Anderson|first5=Patricia L. M.|last5=Lee|first6=Jeremy D.|last6=Wilson|first7=John R.|last7=Krebs|issue=6901|pmid=12198534|bibcode=2002Natur.418..931H|s2cid=4382585}}</ref> and planting native plants in cities benefit the house sparrow, as does establishing urban green spaces.<ref name="Leylandii">{{cite news|author=Adam, David|title=Leylandii may be to blame for house sparrow decline, say scientists|newspaper=The Guardian|date=20 November 2009|access-date=17 January 2009|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2008/nov/20/wildlife-endangeredspecies}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Mukherjee|first=Sarah|title=Making a garden sparrow-friendly|date=20 November 2008|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/7739645.stm|access-date=17 January 2009|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> To raise awareness of threats to the house sparrow, [[World Sparrow Day]] has been celebrated on 20 March since 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article3024688.ece|newspaper=The Hindu|title=Spare a thought for the sparrow |last=Sathyendran |first=Nita |access-date=22 March 2012|date=21 March 2012}}</ref>
To promote conservation, in 2012, the house sparrow was declared as the state bird of Delhi.<ref name="The Hindu-2013">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/kids/save-our-sparrows/article4496787.ece|title=Save our sparrows|date=11 March 2013|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref>

==Cultural associations==
[[File:Bruno Liljefors - House sparrows among the thorns 1886.jpg|thumb|Bruno Liljefors - House sparrows among the thorns (1886)]]
To many people across the world, the house sparrow is the most familiar wild animal and, because of its association with humans and familiarity, it is frequently used to represent the common and vulgar, or the lewd.{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=49, 215}} One of the reasons for the introduction of house sparrows throughout the world was their association with the European homeland of many immigrants.<ref name=Healy/> Birds usually described later as sparrows are referred to in many works of ancient literature and religious texts in Europe and western Asia. These references may not always refer specifically to the house sparrow, or even to small, seed-eating birds, but later writers who were inspired by these texts often had the house sparrow in mind.<ref name=HBW/>{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=49, 215}}<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Shipley|first=A. E.|author-link=Arthur Shipley|title=Sparrow|encyclopedia=[[Encyclopaedia Biblica]]|volume=4|url=https://archive.org/stream/encyclopaediabib04cheyuoft#page/n413/mode/2up/|editor=Cheyne, Thomas Kelley |editor2=Black, J. Sutherland|year=1899|publisher=Morang|location=Toronto}}</ref> In particular, sparrows were associated by the ancient Greeks with [[Aphrodite]], the goddess of love, due to their perceived lustfulness, an association echoed by later writers such as [[Chaucer]] and [[Shakespeare]].<ref name=HBW/>{{sfn|Summers-Smith|2005|pp= 29–35}}{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=49, 215}}<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.credoreference.com/entry/litsymb/sparrow|title=Sparrow|encyclopedia=A Dictionary of Literary Symbols|year=2007}}</ref> Jesus's use of "sparrows" as an example of divine providence in the [[Gospel of Matthew]] also inspired later references, such as that in Shakespeare's ''[[Hamlet]]''{{sfn|Summers-Smith|1963|pp=49, 215}} and the [[hymn]] ''[[His Eye Is on the Sparrow]]''.{{sfn|Todd|2012|pp=56–58}}

